label: Joseph Lyons Diary, Page 117
description: Entries recall finishing SC College, attending parties in Charleston, visiting many Jewish families, mentioning Penina Moise, travelling to Philadelphia, seeing Fanny Kemble & comparing Philadelphia & Charleston women. In Savannah, he studies law, comments on readings and writers, muses on atheism, observances of Jewish holidays and Sabbath, possibility of becoming Hazzan, his poor eyesight and health, his poetry and other topics. After a brief trip to Grahamsville, Purrysburg, Coosawatchie & Pocotaligo, he mentions nullification, Aaron Burr, goes to Effingham County for health, and returns to Charleston. Published in Memoirs of American Jews. Later entries re Civil War era movements of troops.

metadata.label: Transcript
metadata.value: This morning I heard the beginning of an intricate case on the civil side, and I really despaired of ever being a lawyer, but I will halt on that tack or I shall soon be as Blue as the gulf stream. I received this morning through the PO directed to Joseph Lyons Esqr Barrister at Law Savannah Geo, a dam[n]ed nonsensical petition to the US Gov and the People proposing amendments to the Consti[tution] &c. I cant for my soul divine whether it is a hoax or earnest; the direction makes me suspicious, and it resembles the autography of Currell, but then he is not the sort of man so thoughtless or mean as to offer to any one an anonymous slight or insult, so time must make the mystery clear. I recommenced the Cigariad yesterday and wrote 8 stanzas. I could but see my superior facility of Composition on comparison with its progress last year. But I do not pretend to disguise from myself that my Poetry (by courtesy) is either trash or barely mediocre, indeed it is below mediocrity when I recollect that the best American poets are no more than mediocre and where am I, from the station of Percival and Bryant, or even Neale and Pinckney
